{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600544/1930110701/0169.xml":{"full_text":"C-2\nTWO AUTHORS TIE\nFOR HENRY PRIZE\nW. P. Burnett and William M.\nJohn Announced as Joint\nWinners of Award.\n4\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. November 7.\u2014W. P.\nBurnett and William M. John were\nannounced today a* joint winners of\nthe O. Henry Memorial Award for the\nbest short story published In Is2o. by\nan American author In an American\nmagazine.\nIt is the first time In the 12 years\nthat two author* have tied for the first\nprize of SSOO The award to Burnett\nwas made for his \"Dressing Up,\u201d which\nappeared in Harper's for November,\n1929, and John for his \"Neither Jew\nNor Greek.\" published in the Century\nfor August\nSecond prize of $250 was won by\nElizabeth Madox Roberts for \u201cThe Sac\nrifice of the Maidens.\" which was print\ned in Letters, the quarterly magazine\nof the University of Kentucky. A spe\ncial prize of SIOO was awarded Marc\nConnelly for his \u201cCoroner's Inquest.\u201d\npublished In Collier** In February, 1930.\nFOUR MISSING IN FIRE\nWITH $300,000 LOSS\nCapitol Hotel Block at Jamestown,\nN. Dak., Destroyed\u2014Fifth\nPerson Accounted For.\nMy the Associated Press.\nJAMESTOWNfc N. Dak.. November 7.\n\u2014Four persons were unaccounted for\ntoday as a result of fire which de\nstroyed the Capitol Hotel block here\nTuesday night.\nThey are: Mr. and Mrs. A. B.\nSchmidt, K. H. Cook and W; H. Egan.\nA fifth person, Leonard Miller of\nJamestown, also believed missing, was\nlocated yesterday, alive and well.\nThe fire caused damage of $300,000.\nBRAWL STAGED TnToBBY\nOF FRENCH CHAMBER\nGuardsmen Called After Melee In\nvolving Publishers and Dep\nuties.\nBy the Associated Press.\nPARIS, November 7.\u2014The lobby of\nthe Chamber of Deputies was the scene\nof a violent brawl just before the ses\nsion opened yesterday, when Camille\nAymard, director of the Nationalist\nnewspaper La Liberte, got into discus\nsion with a group of Socialist deputies.\nBlows were exchanged.\nA number of windows went broken\nduring the melee, which finally was\ntransferred to the garden of the Palais\nBourbon, where Republican guardsmen\nhad to be called to restart order.\nThe row was a sequel of political\npolemics which have been carried on\nbetween Aymard and Leon Blum, So\ncialist leader, who alao is director of\nthe Socialist newspaper Le Populates.\nKLEIN IS OPTIMISTIC\n1 r 11\n\u25a0ays law t Averages Show Trade\nWill Revive Vast Month,\nISTANBUL, Turkey, November t UP).\n\u2014Julius Klein, Assistant Secretary of\nCommerce for the United States, looks\nfor an American business revival begin\nning next month, he told the American\nChamber of Commerce at a in\nhis honor here yesterday.\n\u201cIf the law of averages work,\" he\n\u2022aid, \"the business crisis should show\nsign* of disappearing next month. The\naverage duration of crises since ISOO\nwas 13 months. Another cause for op\ntimism Is that bustness men through\nout the world are better Informed as a\nresult of the radio and other improved\nmeans of communication.\n\"The present crisis, however. Is not\nconfined to America, but Is world-wide.\nOnly world-wide curative measures can\nbe effective.\u201d\nEWALDS FINGERPRINTED\nNEW YORK. November 7 <Jp.\u2014\nGeorge P. Ewald, former city magis\ntrate, indicted for alleged purchase of\nhis judgeship, and Mrs. Ewald were\nfingerprinted and photographed at po\nlice headquarters yesterday. They sub\nmitted to the formality only after a\ncourt so ordered.\n\u201cI have done nothing to go through\nthis degradation and have my picture\nin the Rogues' Gallery,\" Mrs. Ewald\nsaid. The former magistrate spoke no\nword except to say. in answer to a\nquestion, that he had no occupation\nand was 43 years old.\nA GIFT AT A\nMODERATE j\nPRICE\nI The Smart AW Brownie\nThe new Brownie \u2014ap-\npropriately called \u201cBeau\nBrownie\u201d \u2014ia a small,\n\u25a0\u25a0Uy dressed camera, I\nideal as an inexpensive\ngift or bridge prize.\nColors \u2014bl ue, green, rose,\nblack, tan, with a design\non the front in metal and\ncolored enamels.\nBeau Brovnie has the\nnew Kodak Doublet lena.\nNo* 2 takes 2 1 /i x pic\ntures. Price, $4; with case\n$5.30. No. 2A, 2 V 2 x4H\npictures. Price, ss} with\ncase $6.50.\nEASTMAN KODAK\nSTORES, INC. xr\\\n607-14th Street, N.W. hS/ 1\nTti. District 1591\nBENNETT IS HONORED\nCanadian Premier Vislta Sheffield\nas Imperial Sessions Best.\nLONDON, November 7 UP).\u2014The Im\ngierlft! Conference took yesterday off\nwhile Premier Bennett of Canada went\nto Sheffield to receive the freedom of\nthe city and the other empire premiers\nwent to Birmingham.\nThe delegates will not meet again\nuntil Monday, and their work next\nweek will be Interrupted by Armistice\nday. There Is a possibility that the\ndiscussions may continue into the week\nafter next.\nGIRLS\u2019 DAY\nSaturday\u2014Offering Apparel New in Fashion\u2014Low in Price\n'l $5.95 Girls' Chinchilla $1 to $1.95 Girls'\nj p y b iotH Coat and Hat I I Wash Frocks I\nj, j i\n$16.95 Girls'Pile Fabric Coat Set\nfcompltir wtih n\u201e 51.95 Wool and Velve- j\nA swagger little outfit or N flared skim***\u2019 S?z\u00ab tC 7 $|.69\nfor the girl of 7 to 14 t 0 14 A becoming Style, made with slash\npockets, notch ooilar.JjCut full, nicely \u201cCinderella\" make-which cans frocks of\nyears. Splendid quality, ZK Xh tailored. Sizes 7 to 14. In navv, red, fart color, good quality wash materiel, beau*\n4J I|\\ XTZ (j) j an anf j jr rorn tifully made. These are in prints, stripes, and\nshown in tan and *quir\u00bb k\\[/ lb novelty patterns. Sites Bto 14.\nV .YJihiuiL.. r. e ee t do.) (Second Floor. The Htcht Co\nrelaine. An outfit that V i V w y\nwill delight any little girl J V//\n\u2014it\u2019* smart and practical f\\\n\u25a0\u2014and go warm. n 59c Girls Bloomers\n53.95 Jersey Raincoats \"N azaret h\" \u201cJTf; 34c Cirls's2.9sSweaters\nfun. sizos st\u201e i 6. 1 Union Suits Some With\nI /rrs M